The better world is already here.
COPENHAGEN – For centuries, optimists and pessimists have been discussing the state of the world.
Pessimists see a world in which more people mean less food, where rising resource demand leads to overexploitation and war, and where the increasing production capacity of the past decades results in more pollution and global warming.
One of the sacred texts of the current generation of pessimists, "The Limits to Growth," continues to influence the environmental movement to this day.
Optimists, on the other hand, claim that everything will be better – human health, the standard of living, environmental quality, and so on.
From their opponents, they are seen as "economists of abundance" who trust the market, which allegedly solves all problems.
Instead of picking out facts and stories that fit into a grand narrative of decline or progress, we should try to compare all areas of human existence to see if the world is truly getting better or worse.
Exactly this I have tried to achieve together with 21 leading economists worldwide by developing a rating list for the last 150 years.
In ten areas – including health, education, war, gender ratio, air pollution, climate change, and biodiversity – the economists have answered the same question for each year from 1900 to 2013, as well as making projections up to 2050.
In accordance with classical economic evaluations of all factors from fatalities, health damage, and illiteracy to the destruction of wetlands and increased hurricane risk due to global warming, the economists show the costs of each individual problem.
To assess the magnitude of the problem, it is compared to the total resources available for its solution.
By doing so, the magnitude of the problem becomes apparent as a percentage of the GDP.
And the trends since 1900 are partly surprising.
Let's consider the gender ratio.
In essence, we had almost half of the world's population excluded from production back then.
In 1900, only 15% of the world's workforce were of female gender.
What are the losses that arose from this low proportion?
Even when we account for the higher costs of educating women and the unpaid household work that someone has to do, the losses had a magnitude of at least 17% of the world's GDP in 1900.
Today, with a higher female workforce participation rate and smaller income disparities, the loss is 7% – and is likely to fall to 4% by 2050.
It is likely to be quite surprising that the climate change from 1900 to 2025 will likely bring about a largely growing net benefit, which will increase up to 1.5% of GDP per year.
This lies in the different effects of global warming. If it occurs only moderately, the benefit prevails.
On the one hand, the higher CO2 emissions were a blessing for agriculture, as the gas acts as a fertilizer. This is the largest positive effect, amounting to 0.8% of GDP.
A moderate warming prevents more deaths from cold than it causes additional deaths from heat.
It also reduces heating needs more strongly than it creates new cooling needs, corresponding to a benefit of about 0.4% of GDP.
On the other hand, warming leads to water scarcity, which costs around 0.2% of GDP, and has a negative impact on ecosystems such as wetlands, resulting in a loss of about 0.1%.
As temperatures continue to rise, however, the costs increase and the benefits decline, dramatically reducing the net benefit.
After 2070, the global warming will cause the world net costs, which justifies cost-efficient climate protection today and in the coming decades.
However, the rating list also shows us that the world's largest environmental problem is indoor air pollution, which puts things into the right perspective.
More than three million people die annually from indoor air pollution caused by harmful emissions from cooking and heating, resulting in a loss of 3% of the world's GDP.
But in 1900, these costs accounted for 19% of the GDP, and it is expected to drop to 1% by 2050.
Health indicators have improved the most worldwide.
Until late in the 18th century, human life expectancy had changed little.
The magnitude of the gain since 1900 can hardly be overstated: At that time, the global life expectancy was 32 years, and today it is 69 years (and likely 76 years by 2050).
The most significant factor was the decline in infant mortality.
For example, as recently as 1970, only 5% of infants were vaccinated against measles, tetanus, whooping cough, diphtheria, and polio.
In the year 2000, it was 85%, which has led to the saving of three million lives every year – more than would have been saved through world peace throughout the entire 20th century.
This success has many parents.
The Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation and the GAVI Alliance have committed more than $2.5 billion for vaccines and have pledged a further $10 billion.
Through the efforts of Rotary Club, the World Health Organization, and many others, polio cases have been reduced by 99% since 1979.
In economic terms, the costs of poor health accounted for an astonishing 32% of the world's GDP at the beginning of the 20th century.
Today, they have dropped to about 11% and are expected to halve again by 2050.
Although optimists are not correct in all respects (the loss of biodiversity in the 20th century is likely to cost about 1% of GDP annually, and significantly more in some places), the overall picture is clear.
Most of the examined topics show improvements of 5-20% of GDP.
The overall trend is even more pronounced.
Compared to the resources available to combat them, global problems have dramatically receded.
This does not mean that there are no problems anymore.
Although they have shrunk in areas such as health, education, malnutrition, air pollution, gender inequality, and trade, they are still very large.
But realists should gradually get used to the idea that the world has significantly improved.
Furthermore, the ranking list shows us where the challenges lie for a better 2050.
We should not align our view of the future with the most frightening stories or the loudest interest groups, but rather with objective assessments of where we can achieve the greatest improvements.
